Data analysis

sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with age, number_volunteer_r and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + age + number_volunteer_r + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is weak (conditional R2 = 0.10) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.10. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, number_volunteer_r = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 20.05 (S.E. = 0.94, p < .001, 95% CI [18.21, 21.89]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.02, S.E. = 0.02, p = 0.235, 95% CI [-0.06, 0.01]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-0.47, 0.12])
  • The effect of number volunteer r is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.65, S.E. = 0.35, p = 0.064, 95% CI [-0.04, 1.35]; Std. beta = 0.32, 95% CI [-0.02, 0.66])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.81, S.E. = 0.69, p = 0.241, 95% CI [-0.54, 2.17]; Std. beta = 0.41, 95% CI [-0.28, 1.10])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
